  url = {https://journals.lww.com/00006123-201707000-00041},
  urldate = {2021-12-30},
  abstract = {We do not believe that this kind of publication can have a "casual" reader; however, we are happy to clarify the issues that have been raised. The current study included routine standard microsurgical removal of glioma near the pyramidal tract with application of the prevailing gold standard which was direct electrical subcortical stimulation (DESS), MRI with sequences of T1, T2, fluid-attenuated inversion-recovery (FLAIR), and diffusion tensor imaging (DTI), DTI-based tractography, neuronavigation, neurophysiological monitoring, and intraoperative MRI. 2 Such multimodality microsurgical procedures belong to the daily work of neurosurgeons. The application of intraoperative updated tractography in a prospective design was the unique aspect of the study that facilitated precise comparison of reconstructed fiber tracts with the gold standard of DESS. The judgment about tumor boundary and surrounding white matter tract was based on the clinical decision making of the neuroradiologist, neurol-ogist, and neurosurgeon, mainly considering the gold standard (DESS). Meanwhile the pre-and intraoperative DTI tractography images, used for localization of pyramidal tract, were evaluated in comparison to the gold standard which was DESS, in the setup of a standard microsurgical procedure. 2 The limits of the deterministic algorithm are well understood and discussed in literature. 3-5 Our aim was to test such a tool, which is used in the everyday clinical practice, in a significant large number of neurosurgical departments. When deterministic tractography depicted a 3-dimensional area as corticospinal tract, the result was compared with the real images of T1-weighted MRI and fractional anisotropy (FA) color map, which already indicated neurosurgical anatomy without modification made by software. If the reconstructed DTI-based fiber tracts were far beyond the anatomical perspective, the fibers were excluded manually. Therefore, tools were "everyday methods" with all the shortcomings that others had to deal with as well. There are different approaches and algorithms employed to generate fiber tract representations , which require clear interpretations. 3-5 The challenges and variability of evaluating DTI tractography between different centers were published previously by cooperation of one of our co-authors, as referenced in the letter. 3 Significant differences exist between research tools and their clinical applications, particularly with regard to pre-and intra-operative surgical planning. 3,4 The iPlan Cranial 3.0 software (Brainlab AG, Munich, Germany) is not free source as a pure research tool 4,6 ; however, it is an FDA-approved treatment planning tool. FDA approval indicates further steps that have confirmed accuracy, safety, or reliability of software to be used not only as a research but also as a treatment planning tool. 4,6 Software of DTI tractography require specific parameters to perform fiber depiction, such as the iPlan Cranial 3.0 software(Brainlab AG), which needs FA threshold, minimum fiber length, and task-based functional acquisitions as essentials for image reconstruction. 6,7 The FA threshold and minimum length of fiber tract chosen for the study were in accordance with the previous literature 8,9 and the first author performed the segmentation of the cerebral peduncle. The reliability and interobserver variability in DTI fiber tracking is an important issue; therefore, software-based automatic segmen-tation of the tracts is being established. 10 Blood oxygenation level dependent (BOLD) MRI is a quite standardized technique for functional MRI (fMRI), as explained in the paper. 2 BOLD MRI mapping in iPlan Cranial 3.0 software (Brainlab AG) included task-based functional acquisitions, definition of block design functional task, and creation of 3-dimensional objects from activation areas. 6,7 Analysis and visualization of the fMRI data were performed using Brain Voyager QX (Brain Innovation BV, Maastricht, The Netherlands) software. Slice scan time correction, 3-dimensional motion correction, and correction of linear trend were applied to all functional data using the preprocessing procedures implemented in Brain Voyager QX (Brain Innovation BV) as previously published by the senior author. 11,12 The details are provided elsewhere in literature. 6,7,11,12 Questions have been raised about the validity of statistical methods in fMRI. 13 Any sophisticated modality has several bugs and limitations, which are mostly known and should be controlled. 14,15 Considering all limitations, fMRI has resulted in improved outcomes and reduced postoperative morbidity. 16,17 fMRI is not the only methodology that has clear and serious limitations. Therefore, a multimodal approach is necessary for studying the brain's function and dysfunction, 15 as described in the current study.},
  file = {2017/Amirhossein et al/Amirhossein et al - 2017 - In Reply - Evaluation of Diffusion Tensor Imaging-Based Tractography of the.pdf}
}

